  "prompt": "How are polar covalent bonds formed?",
  "response": "Polar covalent bonds are formed when two atoms with different electronegativities share electrons. Electronegativity is a measure of an atom's ability to attract and hold onto electrons. In a polar covalent bond, the electrons are shared unequally between the atoms.\n\nWhen two atoms with significantly different electronegativities form a covalent bond, the more electronegative atom attracts the shared electrons more strongly. This results in a partial negative charge (\\( \\delta^- \\)) on the more electronegative atom and a partial positive charge (\\( \\delta^+ \\)) on the less electronegative atom. This separation of charges creates a dipole moment, leading to a polar bond.\n\nA common example of a polar covalent bond is the bond between hydrogen and oxygen in a water molecule (H\\(_2\\)O). Oxygen is more electronegative than hydrogen, so the shared electrons spend more time closer to the oxygen atom, resulting in a partial negative charge on the oxygen and partial positive charges on the hydrogen atoms.",
